But the late – and, arguably, great – Sharon Jones was not discovered via a TV talent show or hothoused at a fame school.
It was only at the age of 40 that the erstwhile wedding singer began paying in serious cheques in exchange for belting out songs of love, woe and overcoming.
The first half of Soul of a Woman skews hard towards upbeat songs, such as the hand-clapping Rumors, full of backing vocalists gossiping away.
Sharon Jones obituary Read moreThe second half pulls in organs, forgiveness, orchestral sweeps and, on the self-penned Call on God, the Universal Church of God gospel choir.
“So long, I’m moving on,” Jones sings, ostensibly to the lover she won’t spill one more tear over.